4 Visualization

BIOL 5000

30 October 2020

rr #read in datafile compensation <- read.csv(‘compensation.csv’)

rr #plot data ggplot(compensation, aes(x = Root, y = Fruit)) + geom_point()

rr #add theme ggplot(compensation, aes(x = Root, y = Fruit)) + geom_point() + theme_bw()

rr #add multiple customizations ggplot(compensation, aes(x = Root, y = Fruit, shape = Grazing, color = Grazing)) + geom_point(size = 5) + xlab(Biomass) + ylab(Production) + theme_bw()

rr #box and whisker plots ggplot(compensation, aes(x = Grazing, y = Fruit)) + geom_boxplot() + xlab(treatment) + ylab(Production) + theme_bw()

rr ggplot(compensation, aes(x = Grazing, y = Fruit)) + geom_boxplot() + geom_point(size = 4, color = ‘lightgrey’, alpha = 0.5) + xlab(treatment) + ylab(Production) + theme_bw()

#ggplot2 pre-defined colors browseURL(“http://sape.inf.usi.ch/quick-reference/ggplot2/colour”)

rr #Plotting distribution of a single variable ggplot(compensation, aes(x = Fruit)) + geom_histogram()

rr #Most obvious thing to adjust is bin width: ggplot(compensation, aes(x = Fruit)) + geom_histogram(bins = 10)

rr ggplot(compensation, aes(x = Fruit)) + geom_histogram(binwidth = 15)

rr #faceting ggplot(compensation, aes(x = Fruit)) + geom_histogram(binwidth = 15) + facet_wrap(~Grazing)

rr #save the plot ggsave(.png)

rr #scales and themes in ggplot2 library(gridExtra)

rr # BASE scatterplot eg_scatter <- ggplot(data = compensation, aes(x = Root, y = Fruit)) + geom_point()

rr # BASE box-and-whiskers plot eg_box <- ggplot(data = compensation, aes(x = Grazing, y = Fruit)) + geom_boxplot()

rr grid.arrange(eg_scatter, eg_box, nrow = 1)

rr #plot customizations eg_scatter

rr #add more intuitive axis labels eg_scatter + xlab(Biomass) + ylab(Production)

rr #re-scale the axes (x,y) eg_scatter + xlim(0, 20) + ylim(0, 140)

rr #putting custom text inside figure ; annotate() function eg_scatter + annotate(, x = c(6,8), y = c(105, 25), label = c(up here…,...and text down here))

rr #adjust range of axes, frequency and location of tick marks eg_scatter + scale_x_continuous(limits = c(4, 11), breaks = 4:11)

rr #customizing the colors allocated to each group using scale_colour_manual() layering. ggplot(data = compensation, aes(x = Root, y = Fruit, colour = Grazing)) + geom_point() + scale_colour_manual(values = c(Grazed = , Ungrazed = ))

rr #Scale transformation; one or both of the X-Y axes eg_box + scale_y_continuous(breaks = seq(from = 10, to = 150, by = 20), trans = 10)

rr #modify theme elements; powerful framework for adjusting all the non-aesthetic pieces of a graph eg_scatter + theme( panel.background = element_rect(fill = NA, color = ), panel.grid.minor = element_blank(), panel.grid.major = element_line(color = ) )

#the theme elements you can adjust ? theme #click on help tab to see possible theme elements

rr #Some theme() syntax for axis titles and ticks eg_box + theme( axis.title.x = element_text(colour = , size =rel(2)), axis.text.x = element_text(angle = 45, size = 13, vjust = 0.5))

rr #We use the scale_x_discrete() or scale_y_discrete() function to #customize the labelling of groups eg_box + scale_x_discrete(limits = c(, ), labels = c(, ))

rr #legend position ggplot(compensation, aes(x = Root, y = Fruit, color = Grazing)) + geom_point() + theme(legend.position = )
